Standardizing Scraper Configuration & Pipeline Stabilization
We have successfully eliminated systemic configuration drift across the entire NCAA baseball camp directory pipeline. By establishing a Single Source of Truth and implementing automated consistency guards, we have reached a 100% standardized state.

🏁 Key Accomplishments
1. Centralized Master Configuration
We created 
config.js
 as the absolute authority for all scraper parameters. This file now manages:

BLACKLISTED_DOMAINS: Unified list of low-fidelity and third-party sites.
REJECT_SPORTS: Strict exclusions for non-baseball programs.
OFFICIAL_PLATFORMS: Priority list for camp registration portals.
Regex Patterns: Standardized DATE_PATTERNS, COST_PATTERN, and EMAIL_PATTERN used across all logic.
Logic Helpers: Shared functions for sport detection and platform verification.
2. Elimination of Code Drift
We refactored 11 core scripts and utilities to remove independent, hardcoded constants. All active logic now imports directly from the central module:

Core Scrapers: smart_extract.js, deep_url_audit.js
Extraction Logic: extract_camp_details.js, extract_verify.js
Test Suite: data_integrity_audit.js, test_llm_issues.js, test_extraction.js, scrub_bad_data.js, verify_database_integrity.js, test_v7.js, purge_blacklisted.js
3. Automated Regression Guard
We implemented 
test_config_consistency.js
, a static analysis tool that scans the entire codebase to detect any future attempts to hardcode shared configuration tokens.

